'''Mimaki-Hime''' (御間城姫) was Empress Consort of Japan from 97 BC to 29 BC, and then Empress Dowager from 29 BC to an unknown date.<ref>Anston, p. 150 (Vol. 1)</ref><ref>Anston, p. 165 (Vol. 1)</ref>

== Life ==
The [[Nihon Shoki]] tells us her children are Emperor Suinin, Izanomawaka, Kunikatahime, Chijitsukuyamatohime, and Yamatohiko.<ref name=":2">Aston. W.G. (1896) “Nihongi Volume 1: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to AD697”. Tuttle Publishing.</ref><ref name=":0">Yasumaro. O, translated by Gustav Heldt. (2014) “Kojiki. An Account of Ancient Matters”. New York: Columbia University Press.</ref><ref name=":1">Chamberlain, B. H. (1932) “Translation of the Kojiki.” Kobe: J.L. Thompson & Co.</ref> where as in the [[Kojiki]] she has another child named Igahime.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> The Nihon shoki also states that she had her children with Emperor Sujin before her ascension as Empress Consort.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |title=Mimakihime • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/mimakihime/ |access-date=2024-03-10 |website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |language=en-GB}}</ref> While the Nihon Shoki does not give a name for her father, the Kojiki gives her father's name as Prince Ohiko.<ref>Ponsonby, F. (1959) “The Imperial House of Japan.” Kyoto: Ponsonby Memorial Society.</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /> 
[[File:大彦命 Ōhiko no mikoto 日本百将伝.jpg|alt=Mimaki-Hime's father, Prince Ohiko.|left|thumb|455x455px|Mimaki-Hime's father, Prince Ohiko.]]

